==Events==
The following major [[chess tournament]]s took place in 1988:

===Grandmasters Association World Cup===
The [[Grandmasters Association]] held six World Cup tournaments over 1988 and 1989, with some of the world's best players invited.  The first three of these tournaments were held in 1988.

* 1 April – 22 April: The first tournament was held in [[Brussels]] and won by Karpov with 11/16, ahead of [[Valery Salov]] with 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chesscollection?cid=1015865|title=Brussels WC 1988|author=www.chessgames.com|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>
* 14 June – 3 July: The second tournament was held in [[Belfort]], [[France]] and won by Kasparov with 11½/15, ahead of Karpov with 10½.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chesscollection?cid=1015937|title=Belfort WC 1988|author=www.chessgames.com|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>
* 3 October – 24 October: The third tournament was held in [[Reykjavík]] and was again won by Kasparov, with 11/17.  Beliavsky was second, with 10½/15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chesscollection?cid=1015916|title=Reykjavík WC 1988|author=www.chessgames.com|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>

===28th Chess Olympiad===

The [[28th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Thessaloniki]], [[Greece]] was held between 12 November and 30 November.  It was won by the [[USSR]], ahead of [[England]] in second and the [[Netherlands]] in third.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/1988/1988in.html|title=28th Chess Olympiad, Thessaloniki|author=www.olimpbase.org|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>

The gold medal on the first board was won by Kasparov of USSR with 8½/10.  [[Lajos Portisch]] of [[Hungary]] was second, also scoring 8½, but from 11 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/1988/1988in.html#medals|title=28th Chess Olympiad, individual medalists|author=www.olimpbase.org|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>

The [[Women's Chess Olympiad]] was held alongside the open tournament.  The winners were Hungary, ahead of the USSR and [[Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpbase.org/1988w/1988te14.html|title=28th Chess Olympiad, women's tournament|author=www.olimpbase.org|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>

===Other major tournaments===
*23 February – 8 March: The [[Linares chess tournament|Linares tournament]] was won by Timman with 8½/11, ahead of Beliavsky with 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chesscollection?cid=1012173|title=Linares 1988|author=www.chessgames.com|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>
*6 September – 28 September: The 12th [[Tilburg chess tournament|Tilburg tournament]] was won by Karpov with 10½/14, ahead of Short with 8½.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.delaire.pagesperso-orange.fr/Tournois/Tilburg.htm|title=Tilburg 1988|language=French|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>
*December 1988 – January 1989: The [[Reggio Emilia chess tournament|Reggio Emilia tournament]] was won by [[Mikhail Gurevich (chess player)|Mikhail Gurevich]] with 6½/9, ahead of [[Kiril Georgiev]] and [[Ulf Andersson]] Ivanchuk with 5½.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ippogrifoscacchi.it/tdc_storia/data/1988-89.htm|title=Reggio Emilia 1988/89|language=Italian|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>
* The [[Wijk aan Zee chess tournament|Wijk aan Zee tournament]] was won by Karpov with 9/13, ahead of Anderssen with 8½.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coruschess.com/tournament.php?id=51|title=Wijk aan Zee 1988|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>

