A '''fly ball pitcher''' is a type of [[baseball pitcher]] who produces an above-average number of [[Batted ball|fly balls]], typically by keeping his [[fastball]] high up in the strike zone and relying on late movement to cause the batter to be unable to make solid contact. This designation is constructed around the [[ground ball fly ball ratio]], which measures how frequently a pitcher gets batters out on fly balls versus ground balls.

The downside of a fly ball pitcher is that, in a ballpark where the design tends to favor hitters over pitchers (an example being [[Yankee Stadium]]), a fly ball pitcher will tend to give up more home runs, resulting in a higher [[earned run average]].

Examples include pitchers [[Sid Fernandez]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-08-11/sports/1995223063_1_sid-fernandez-orioles-camden-yards|title='Sid Sez': He likes the NL better|accessdate=2014-09-14|date=1995-08-11|work=[[Baltimore Sun]]|author=Rosenthal, Ken}}</ref> [[Ted Lilly]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/fantasy/baseball/flb/story?id=5426501|title=Ted Lilly, Ryan Theriot to Dodgers|accessdate=2014-09-14|date=2010-07-31|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Cockcroft, Tristan H.}}</ref>, [[Chris Young (pitcher)|Chris Young]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/fantasy-baseball-today/24610428/chris-young-breakout-or-fakeout|title=Chris Young: Breakout or fakeout?|accessdate=2014-09-14|date=2014-07-07|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=White, R. J.}}</ref> and [[Marco Estrada (baseball)|Marco Estrada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationalpost.com/sports/baseball/mlb/toronto-blue-jays-pitcher-marco-estrada-is-getting-kind-of-tired-of-the-doubters/wcm/5993b1e5-5f57-4567-93ba-48ef3b8eebae|title=Toronto Blue Jays pitcher Marco Estrada is getting 'kind of tired' of the doubters|accessdate=2017-07-31|date=2015-09-18|publisher=National Post|author=Lott, J.}}</ref>

