{{Infobox swimming venue |name = Nassau County Aquatics Center |logo = |logosize = |logocaption = |image = File:Nassau County Aquatic Center.jpg |imagesize = |caption = Nassau County Aquatics Center in May 2007 |fullname = Nassau County Aquatics Center at Eisenhower Park |nicknames = |city = [[East Meadow, NY]], United States |capacity = 3,300<ref name=NYT/> |built = 1998 |opened = 1998 |construction cost = $30 million USD<ref name=NYT/> |architects = |home clubs = Excel Swimming, High Dive Champions, Long Island Aquatic Club, Long Island Divers, New York Dive Club |poolname = |length = 68m |width = 25m |deep = 0-25ft |lanes = 10 |}}
The '''Nassau County Aquatics Center''' is an aquatic facility in [[East Meadow, NY]]. It is considered the largest Olympic-sized single-tank pool in North America.<ref name=nydn>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/center-life-aquatic-article-1.241810|title=Center of the life aquatic|author=Richard Weir|publisher=New York Daily News|date=August 26, 2007|access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> At least 16 world records in swimming have been set in the facility.<ref name=nydn/> It was built in 1998 for the Goodwill Games. Since the Goodwill Games in 1998, it has hosted numerous swimming championships and high level competitions including the [[USA Swimming]] National Championship, [[NCAA]] National Championship, and [[FINA]] World Cup. The Center is 80,000 square feet with a 68m pool and three moveable bulkheads to accommodate SCM, SCY, and LCM competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nassaucountyny.gov/1769/Aquatic-Center|title=Aquatic Center|publisher=Nassau County|access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> In 2002, [[Natalie Coughlin]] set multiple world records during the FINA World Cup at the center.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/01/nyregion/nassau-pool-albatross-or-olympic-opportunity.html?pagewanted=all|title=Nassau Pool: Albatross Or Olympic Opportunity?|author=Allan Richter|publisher=New York Times|date=December 1, 2002|access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> In 2002 it was reported that the pool had lost millions of dollars.<ref name=NYT/> Dave Ferris was aquatics director in 2002, he reportedly questioned the reported losses, stating that "I don't believe expenses on the building are completely clear at this time".<ref name=NYT/> In 2011, the facility underwent a renovation after a 40lbs light fixture fell about 55 feet into the swimming pool.<ref name=lih>{{cite web|url=http://liherald.com/stories/Renovation-on-tap-for-the-Nassau-County-Aquatic-Center,30312?page=1&|title=Renovation on tap for the Nassau County Aquatic Center|author=Mike Caputo|date=January 26, 2011|access-date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> Since 2011 it had also been proposed to build an additional outdoor 50m pool adjacent to the existing facility.<ref name=lih/>
